eceased","1050–1098":"1050–1098","1055–1090":"1055–1090","1090":"1090","after 1090":"after 1090","1055":"1055","1098":"1098","1120":"1120","1152":"1152","1084":"1084","1050":"1050","1171":"1171","1105":"1105","1101":"1101","about 1101":"about 1101","about 1100":"about 1100","Meaux, Seine-et-Marne, Île-de-France, France":"Meaux, Seine-et-Marne, France","La Ferté-Saint-Samson, Seine-Maritime, Normandy, France":"La Ferté-Saint-Samson, Seine-Maritime, Normandy, France","Meaux-Sud, Meaux, Seine-et-Marne, France":"Meaux-Sud, Meaux, Seine-et-Marne, France","Saint-Quentin, Aisne, Picardie, France":"Saint-Quentin, Aisne, Picardie, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Dit","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Chun, Hin, Kwan, Fung, Wai, Yau, Chi, Chi Shing, Chow, Hon, Hong, Kit Man.  Korean Chung, Pak.","Chinese: Cantonese form of the surname 薛, see   Xue  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Xue","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Hong, Jian, Hua, Liang, Wei, Yuan, Biao, Chun, Fei, Lixin, Ming, Qi, Min, Tian, Yiming.  Vietnamese Lan, Hao, Huan.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 薛, originally denoting a ‘type of grass’ in ancient Chinese: (i) from Xue (薛), the name of an ancient state (originally located in Shandong province) dating back to the Xia dynasty (2070–1600  BC ). After it was annexed by the state of Chu during the Western Zhou dynasty (1046–771  BC ), the name of the state was adopted as a surname. (ii) from the placename Xue (薛), the name of a fief (located in Shandong province) granted to Meng Chang Jun (Lord Meng Chang), a famous prince of the state of Qi, known as one of “the four princes during the Warring States period (475–221  BC )”. (iii) adopted as the surname by the Chi Gan (叱干) family from the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (iv) borne by descendants of Xue Huai Yi (薛懷義), a famous general of the Tang dynasty (618–907  AD )."]}]},{"name":"Geoffroy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Pierre, Camille, Christophe, Emile, Jean-Marie, Laurent, Normand, Sylvian, Telesphore.","French: from the Old French personal name <i>Geuffrei</i>, <i>Geffroi</i>. See   Jeffrey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Geoffrion","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Lucien, Andre, Camille, Damien, Emile, Francoise, Pierre.","French: from a pet form of the personal name   Geoffroy  . Compare   Joffrion  ."]},{"name":"Gioffre","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Rocco, Carmelo, Alfredo, Antonino, Carmela, Gaetano, Giacomo, Giovanna, Giuseppe, Rino, Salvatore.","Italian (<b>Gioffré</b>): from the personal name<i>Gioffré</i>, a borrowing from French (see   Geoffroy  )."]},{"name":"Geffrard","meanings":["French and Haitian: from a hypocoristic of the French personal name <i>Geffroy</i>, a variant of   Geoffroy  . This surname is very rare in France. It was brought to the US from Haiti."]},{"name":"Jeffrey","meanings":["English and Scottish: from the common Middle English and Older Scots personal name <i>Geffrey</i>, a borrowing of Old French <i>Geuffrei</i>, <i>Jeufrei</i>, <i>Jefrei</i>, <i>Gosfrei</i>, <i>Jofrei</i>. The principal source of the Old French forms was probably ancient Germanic <i>Gautfrid</i>, from an ethnic name + <i>frithu</i> ‘peace’. It was commonly Latinized in early documents as <i>Gaufridus</i> or <i>Galfridus</i>, but also as <i>Goisfridus</i> or <i>Gosfridus</i>. Anglo-Norman French <i>Jofreith</i>, <i>Jofrei</i> lies behind the English surnames <i>Joffrey</i> and <i>Joffray</i>, which are recorded in the late nineteenth century, but may now be extinct."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"la","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Hung, Cuong, Anh, Thanh, Ha, Hoang, Tuan, Chau, Hao, Hien, Hoa, Hue, Nam, Phong, Sinh, Tuong, Min, Tam, Tanh, Thai, Tham, Tinh, Yeong.  Chinese Hong, Hang, Sang, Tong, Chan, Chi, Hwa Ja, Hyung, Kam, Ki Bong, Kin, Man.","Vietnamese: from the Chinese surname 羅, see   Luo   1.","Vietnamese (<b>Lã</b>): from the Chinese surname 呂, see   Lu   6 and 3 below."],"variants":[{"name":"Luo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Wei, Jian, Yi, Ping, Yong, Zhen, Feng, Hong, Ming, Jin, Bin, Chen, Hai, Lan, Min, Huan, Hung, Shen, Tian.","Chinese:","Mandarin form of the surname 羅, meaning ‘net for catching birds’ or ‘to collect’ in Chinese: (i) from Luo (羅), the name of an ancient state (located in present-day Hubei province). After it was annexed by the state of Chu during the early Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ), people from the state migrated southwards and adopted Luo (羅) as their surname. (ii) from the Po Duo Luo (破多羅) and Chi Luo (叱羅) families from the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China, who changed their original surnames to 羅 during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (iii) from the personal name Hu Se Luo (斛瑟羅), leader of an ancient Turkic tribe who are believed to have migrated to China during the Tang dynasty (618–907  AD ). His descendants inherited his name Hu Se Luo (斛瑟羅) as their surname and shortened it to 羅 during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (iv) from the name of one of the seven families from the Bandun Man, an ethnic group residing in ancient southwestern China (located mainly in present-day Sichuan province)."]}]},{"name":"Ferté","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Dino, Domenic, Domenico, Salvatore, Santo, Saverio.","Italian (<b>Berté</b>): probably from a short form of the personal name <i>Bertiere</i>, a derivative of   Berto  .","German: variant of   Bert  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Berto","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Mario, Jose Cruz, Manuel, Virgilio.  Italian Dario, Mauro, Vito.","Italian: from the personal name <i>Berto</i>, a short form ofany of various ancient Germanic names formed with <i>bert</i> (from<i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’), for example <i>Alberto</i>,<i>Gilberto</i>, <i>Norberto</i>, <i>Roberto</i>, <i>Umberto</i>.","Hungarian (<b>Bertó</b>): from a pet form of the personalname <i>Bertalan</i>, Hungarian form of   Bartholomew  ."]}]},{"name":"Geoffroy","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Germanic (Frankish and Lombard) origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. It was in regular use among the counts of Anjou, ancestors of the English royal house of Plantagenet, who were descended from Geoffrey Plantagenet, Count of Anjou (  1113–51 ). It was a particularly popular name in England and France in the later Middle Ages; notable bearers in England include the poet  Geoffrey Chaucer  (  <i>c.</i>1340–1400 ) and in Wales the chronicler  Geoffrey  of Monmouth (  d. 1155 ). The original form and meaning of the name is disputed. According to one theory, it is merely a variant of   Godfrey ;  others derive the first part from the Germanic word <i>gawia</i> ‘territory’, <i>walah</i> ‘stranger’, or <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’. Medieval forms can be found to support all these theories, and it is possible that several names have fallen together, or that the name was subjected to reanalysis by folk etymology at an early date."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Bright’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Meaux","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andrus, Amede, Camille, Eves, Maudry, Michel, Pierre, Theogene.","French:","variant of <b>Maux</b>, probably a nickname from a variant of <i>mal</i> ‘bad’ (see   Mau  ), or a habitational name from a place called Maux or perhaps Meaux (see 2 below)."],"variants":[{"name":"Mau","meanings":["Pet form of   Maria   and   Margit  , now also used as an independent given name and as an element of compound names such as <i>Mai-Britt</i>, <i>Mai-Lis</i>, <i>Anne-Mai</i>, and <i>Britt-Mai</i>."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sire Geoffroy de Meaux Dit Geoffroy de la Ferté was born in 1090, in Meaux, Seine-et-Marne, France, his father, Etienne de Meaux, was 41 and his mother, Ermentrude de Pierrefonds, was 36. He married Constance De Vermandois about 1100, in Saint-Quentin, Aisne, Picardie, France. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. He died in 1152, in his hometown, at the age of 62."},"et":{"1090–1152":"1090–1152","1084–1101":"1084–1101","1105–1171":"1105–1171","1120–Female":"1120–Surnud","1050–1098":"1050–1098","1055–1090":"1055–1090","1090":"1090","after 1090":"pärast 1090","1055":"1055","1098":"1098","1120":"1120","1152":"1152","1084":"1084","1050":"1050","1171":"1171","1105":"1105","1101":"1101","about 1101":"umbes 1101","about 1100":"umbes 1100","Meaux, Seine-et-Marne, Île-de-France, France":"Meaux, Seine-et-Marne, Prantsusmaa","La Ferté-Saint-Samson, Seine-Maritime, Norm